A `OUTPUT` parameter is still an input parameter; there is no such thing as a &quot;non-input&quot; parameter with Stored Procedures.  You still need to pass a variable to the parameter, as the value of the `OUTPUT` parameter will be assigned to that variable once the SP completes.

If you were using T-SQL to execute the SP, it would look like this:

    CREATE PROC dbo.MyProc @MyParam int OUTPUT AS
    BEGIN
    
        SET @MyParam = 1;
    END;
    GO
    
    DECLARE @MyParam int;
    EXEC dbo.MyProc @MyParam OUTPUT;
    
    PRINT @MyParam; --1

